Koninkrijk"},"en":{"ABT    1337–":"about 1337–Deceased","1337–Male":"1337–Deceased","1414–Male":"1414–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1154–Female":"1154–Deceased","1378–Male":"1378–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","ABT    1378":"about 1378","1414":"1414","1337":"1337","1378":"1378","1154":"1154","ABT    1337":"about 1337","of,Llannerch-y-medd,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","of Llwydiarth,Llannerch-y-medd,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hywel","type":"LAST","meanings":["A Welsh name. Some write the name Hoel, which they render 'lordly;' if so, it may come from huail, a vice-regent, regent. Arthur derives the surname Howell from Corn. -Brit, houl, the sun; and he adds, high, exalted.' But Hywel is rather from hywel, conspicuous."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ieuan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ieuan ap Hywel was born about 1337, in Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Hywel ap Twna and Efa ferch Thomas. He had at least 1 son with Morfudd ferch Dafydd."},"et":{"ABT    1337–":"umbes 1337–Surnud","1337–Male":"1337–Surnud","1414–Male":"1414–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1154–Female":"1154–Surnud","1378–Male":"1378–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","ABT    1378":"umbes 1378","1414":"1414","1337":"1337","1378":"1378","1154":"1154","ABT    1337":"umbes 1337","of,Llannerch-y-medd,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingd